{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Design decisions affecting accessibility: edit and delete",
    "content": "Heydon, heads up — Steve Schoger and I just worked through some component design decisions. Two that directly affect accessibility:\n\n**Delete button: always visible, visually quiet.** I pushed back on hover-to-reveal. The delete affordance will be a small muted icon on every todo item, always visible. This is better for keyboard and screen reader users too — no need to discover a hidden action.\n\n**Edit: visible pencil icon rather than click-to-edit.** Steve originally proposed clicking the todo title to enter edit mode. I flagged that this is not discoverable for most users. We're going with a visible pencil icon instead. This is also much better for you — a clear, focusable button with a label like \"Edit [todo title]\" that screen readers can announce. Click-to-edit on a text element would be a nightmare for assistive tech.\n\nBoth the edit and delete buttons should be proper `<button>` elements with accessible labels. The icons are visual affordances; the labels are for everyone who can't see them.\n\nWanted to make sure you're aligned before the team starts building these components."
  }
}
